  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "What’s your favorite dish to cook at home?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hmm, I don’t cook much, but when I do, I love making pav bhaji. It’s quick and tasty. What about you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Pav bhaji is a Mumbai classic, I get it! Quick, messy, and perfect. What’s your favorite way to eat it, with aloo tikki or plain?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Honestly, I prefer it plain with pav and maybe some chutney. Sometimes I add aloo tikki if I have it, but not always. How about you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Plain with pav and chutney sounds just right, simple and satisfying. I usually go for that too. What’s your favorite chutney to pair with it. Green, red, or both?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I usually go for both — green and red chutney together. They balance each other out. But sometimes, if I’m in a hurry, I just take red. Acha, by the way, have you ever tried making pav bhaji at home?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Making pav bhaji at home sounds fun, but I stick to the street vendors most of the time. What’s your go to recipe if you ever make it. Basic or with extra spices?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I usually stick to the basic mix of veggies and spices — potatoes, peas, carrots, and that classic pav bhaji masala. Sometimes I add a bit of garlic or green chilies for extra kick. But mostly, less is more for me."
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Got it, simple base with a little kick when you want it. Street style, but home made. What’s your favorite place to eat it in Mumbai?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hmm, there’s this one small eatery near my office — it’s not fancy, but the pav bhaji is spot on. A bit of mess, but I don’t mind. You should try it if you come to Mumbai!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "That sounds like my kind of spot, messy and real! What other Mumbai street food do you love, if I may ask. Something besides pav bhaji?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Vada pav is another Mumbai staple I can't get enough of. The combination of a spicy potato vada and that soft pav is unbeatable. And if I'm out with friends, we often go for bhel puri or sev puri — crispy, tangy, and just so much fun to eat. But let's be real, I'm always back for more pav bhaji. 😄"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Vada pav and the street food magic of Mumbai, you hit the right notes! Speaking of fun to eat, what’s your favorite part about sharing these with friends, the food or the mess?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Both, honestly. The food is amazing, but the mess makes it fun — laughing while trying not to drop anything, the tangy chutney dripping everywhere, you know? It’s not just about the taste, it’s the vibe. But today, I’m just annoyed because I spilled my coffee again. Rude!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "That vibe sounds like the real Mumbai charm, messy, loud, and full of life. Spilled coffee, ouch! Any chance you'll switch to tea today, or is coffee still the fight?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Maybe tea today, but I’m not a big tea person. Coffee is just part of my routine, even if I spill it half the time. Guess I’ll grab a pav bhaji and tea to balance it out. Less mess, maybe. 😅"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Tea and pav bhaji, a Mumbai dream team, even if the tea is just for balance! Will you go for the classic green tea or something spiced, like masala chai?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Masala chai, no doubt. The spices warm you up, and it’s just so much more satisfying than plain tea. Plus, it goes well with the richness of pav bhaji. But I might end up spilling that too. Ugh."
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Masala chai with pav bhaji, warm, rich, and totally worth the potential spill! What’s your go to spice mix for it, cinnamon and cardamom or something else?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I usually go for cinnamon, cardamom, and a touch of ginger — that’s the classic combo. Sometimes I add cloves or fennel seeds for extra flavor. But honestly, if it’s good and spicy, I’m happy. Let’s just hope I don’t spill it. 😅"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Cinnamon, cardamom, and ginger, the perfect trio for that comforting kick! I get the hope for no spills, what’s your trick to avoid dropping things while eating, if you have one?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Honestly? No real trick. I eat slowly, but when the food is good, I get distracted. Maybe I should use both hands — one for the pav, one for the chutney. But no, I’m still a spill risk. Coffee. Tea. Everything. Ugh. Thanks for listening, though. Need to get back to work. Talk later!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Spill risk for the win, but at least the food is worth it! Take your time, and good luck with work, spill free or not, you’ve got this!\""
    }
  ],
